I""<p>Reward systems are internal to one’s body. They’re shaped by one’s <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/affect-reflects-ideological-structures">belief system</a>, among others. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memetic-psychotherapy-equips-prefrontal-areas-with-mental-tools-for-managing-limbic-friction">Memetic psychotherapy</a> can shape one’s <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/internalizing-beliefs-incurs-ideological-debt">belief system</a>. This entails that reward systems can be shaped non-invasively. The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/objective-functions-are-deceptive">objective function</a> of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/carbon-chauvinism-denies-artificial-general-intelligence">biological creatures</a> is malleable.</p>
